---
description: "Methodology rules for benchmarking/eval scripts against small local models — read before writing or trusting any eval in scripts/"
globs: ["scripts/bench_*.py", "scripts/eval_*.py", "scripts/needle_training/**/*",
        "docs/phase0-measurements.md", "docs/PHASE0_FINDINGS_SUMMARY.md"]
alwaysApply: false
---
Every rule below cost real time during Phase-0/0.5 benchmarking — each one
traces to a specific wrong number that got reported before the root cause
was found. Full incident writeup: `docs/phase0-measurements.md` §16.

**Verify the environment before declaring something blocked or unreachable.**
`ssh <host>` failing to resolve is evidence the alias doesn't resolve from
here — it is not evidence you aren't already on the target machine. Check
`hostname`, `nvidia-smi`, and the expected local paths directly before
reporting "no access."

**Thinking-capable models: suppress reasoning at the server level, not with
a prompt convention.** A `/no_think` (or similar) text suffix is not a
reliable switch — it worked on one checkpoint (Qwen3-1.7B) and silently
failed on two others (Qwen3.6-35B-A3B, and a specific `qwen3-4b.gguf`
conversion), which kept reasoning regardless and left `message.content`
empty at any token budget. Use llama-server's own `--reasoning off` (or
`--reasoning-budget 0`) flag when booting the eval server. Never conclude a
model is "bad at X" from an empty or truncated response without first
checking whether the response was still inside `<think>`/`reasoning_content`
when it got cut off.

**Thinking-capable models need a real token budget before judging quality,
even with reasoning suppression attempted.** Use ≥1024 tokens as an eval
floor, ≥4096 for genuinely hard reasoning/coding-diagnosis prompts. A
256-300 token budget measures truncation, not correctness — treat any
result from an under-budgeted run as void, not as a quality finding.

**Small models (sub-2B parameters) need worked few-shot examples, not just
instructions.** A bare category list, a one-line format spec, or an
abstract "pick the most precise match" instruction is not enough signal at
this size. Write 2-7 worked examples that target the model's *actual*
observed confusion cases (read the failures first, then write examples for
those specific pairs/categories) — generic examples that don't address the
real confusion don't move the number.

**Audit scoring/extraction code with the same suspicion as model output.**
Before trusting a low accuracy number, check whether the label-extraction
logic has a substring-order bug: if one label is a substring of another
(e.g. `"chat"` inside `"chit_chat"`), a naive `if label in text` scan
checked in the wrong order silently misscores correct model output. Any
classifier scorer over a label set with this property must match
longest-label-first with word boundaries (or require an exact match), not
plain substring containment.

**Design the rubric around the deterministic post-processing that will
actually run, not the model's raw compliance.** Don't score a model
pass/fail on hitting an exact numeric range (e.g. "must be 5-8 words") when
the real pipeline can deterministically fix one direction of the violation
(truncate an overlong output) but not the other (can't lengthen a too-short
one). If the shipped code truncates, the rubric's upper bound should be
"truncates to ≤N," not "must already be ≤N," and there should be no
artificial lower bound at all — a short-but-correct output is not a defect.

**A plausible mitigation still has to be measured, not assumed.**
Well-known patterns (e.g. embedding-based tool-retrieval pre-filtering
before a small dispatcher picks a tool) can still make things worse in a
specific setup — e.g. if the retrieval step itself has non-trivial miss
recall, every miss is an unrecoverable failure that a fix targeting a
different bottleneck won't show up as an improvement for. Run the
comparison and report a negative result honestly rather than assuming the
standard fix worked.

**Give concurrent background evals distinct ports explicitly.** Don't rely
on a script's default `--port` when launching more than one eval in the
background at once — two servers racing for the same port produces a
zombie process and a garbage/empty result for whichever one loses the bind,
which looks like a model failure if you don't notice the port collision.

**When comparing model sizes, verify the smaller model's fix actually
transfers before concluding "bigger is better/worse."** A flag or prompt
trick that works on one checkpoint is not guaranteed to work on a
same-family model at a different size or from a different
conversion/quantization pipeline — confirm the fix (e.g. `--reasoning off`)
actually takes effect on the specific gguf under test (check the raw
response body, not just the summary metric) before drawing a
capacity conclusion from a comparison.
